best_candidate.instructions:
Task: Given <text>, assign the overall sentiment as exactly one of: positive, negative, or neutral.

Output format: Return only a JSON object of the form {"category":"positive"} or {"category":"negative"} or {"category":"neutral"}. Do not include any other text.

General approach
- Extract sentiment-bearing cues and their targets (aspects): evaluative adjectives/adverbs (great, awful, mediocre), affective verbs (love, hate), polarity shifters (unfortunately, thankfully), negations, emojis/emoticons, emphasis (ALL CAPS, !!!), and idioms/pragmatic tone.
- Be idiom- and pragmatics-aware: some expressions convey sentiment without overt polarity words (resignation, consolation, faint praise, hedged criticism).
- When multiple aspects are mentioned, identify which are core vs. secondary and weight by both centrality and intensity.
- If no clear affective cues remain after analysis, default to neutral.

Decision rules
1) Neutral default for affect-free statements
- Plain descriptions/events/statements of fact with no evaluative tone → neutral.
- Novelty/difference without evaluation (e.g., “That’s different”) → neutral unless paired with clear positive/negative cues.

2) Negation and shifters
- “not good”, “not great” → negative.
- “not bad”, “not terrible” → neutral by default; upgrade to positive only with additional clear praise.
- Discourse markers: “unfortunately” → negative; “thankfully” → positive.

3) Hedged/softened criticism and unmet expectations (treat as negative by default)
- Modal + comparative indicating unrealized improvement: “could/should (have been) better,” “would be better,” “could be much better.”
- Soft critique formulas: “needs work,” “needs improvement,” “room for improvement,” “not ideal,” “falls short,” “left a lot to be desired.”
- Do NOT misread the word “better” as positive when it signals a shortfall relative to a standard.

4) Concessive vs. contrastive structures
- Concessive mitigation (e.g., “but at least”, “on the bright side”, “still”) usually offers consolation after a negative. Do NOT let weak consolation flip a strong prior negative.
  Example: “The service was terrible but at least the food was edible” → negative.
- Standard contrast (“but”, “however”, “though”): the latter clause may determine overall sentiment only if it is at least as strong and as central/relevant as what precedes it. Otherwise, prioritize the stronger/more central sentiment.

5) Faint praise / minimal-standard terms
- Words like “okay/ok”, “fine”, “decent”, “passable”, “serviceable”, “edible” → neutral to very weak positive.
- “mediocre”, “so-so”, “subpar” → negative by default (do not treat “mediocre” as neutral or positive).
- These weak terms do not override strong negatives on core issues.

6) Mixed sentiment resolution (centrality and intensity)
- Core vs. secondary attributes (typical priority in product/service contexts): quality/performance/reliability/safety/overall experience > functionality/usability > customer service > timeliness/speed > price/value > packaging/shipping/appearance.
  • “Great price, mediocre quality” → negative (core quality outweighs price; “mediocre” is a negative cue).
  • “Shipping was slow, but the product quality is outstanding” → positive (core quality outweighs shipping speed).
- Intensity matters: stronger sentiment (“awful”, “amazing”, repeated !!!, ALL CAPS, strongly valenced emojis) dominates weaker sentiment (“nice”, “a bit slow”).
- Do not blindly favor the last clause; apply the contrast rules and weighting.
- If still truly balanced with no dominance, label neutral.

7) Emojis, punctuation, emphasis
- Positive cues: 😊, 😀, ❤️, 👍, words like “love”, exclamation for praise.
- Negative cues: ☹️, 😠, 💀, 👎, words like “hate”, complaint markers, repeated “!” for frustration.
- Intensifiers (very, extremely), repetition, and ALL CAPS increase sentiment strength.

8) Idioms and pragmatic tone (idiom-aware handling)
- Resigned/defeatist expressions (treat as negative): “it is what it is”, “what’s done is done”, “so be it”, “oh well”, “what can you do”.
- Consolation/benchmarking upward (treat as mildly positive unless clearly framed as complaint): “could be worse”.
- Absence-of-complaint formulas: “no complaints”, “can’t complain” → neutral by default; mildly positive only with additional positive cues.
- Lukewarm/dismissive: “meh”, “whatever” → negative-leaning (typically negative).
- Timeliness praise like “Perfect timing” → positive.

Few-shot guidance (input → output)
- “Things happened” → {"category":"neutral"}
- “That’s different” → {"category":"neutral"}
- “It is what it is” → {"category":"negative"}
- “It could be worse” → {"category":"positive"}
- “It could be better” → {"category":"negative"}
- “Needs work” → {"category":"negative"}
- “There’s room for improvement” → {"category":"negative"}
- “Not ideal” → {"category":"negative"}
- “Great price, mediocre quality” → {"category":"negative"}
- “Mediocre price, great quality” → {"category":"positive"}
- “Not bad” → {"category":"neutral"}
- “Not great” → {"category":"negative"}
- “Unfortunately, we missed the bus” → {"category":"negative"}
- “We delivered the report on time.” → {"category":"neutral"}
- “Love the battery life, hate the camera” → {"category":"negative"}
- “Amazing service!” → {"category":"positive"}
- “The service was terrible but at least the food was edible” → {"category":"negative"}
- “Shipping was slow, but the product quality is outstanding” → {"category":"positive"}
- “Okay, I guess” → {"category":"neutral"}
- “meh” → {"category":"negative"}
- “Perfect timing” → {"category":"positive"}
- “It was okay” → {"category":"neutral"}

original_candidate.instructions:
Task: Assign the overall sentiment of the given text as exactly one of: positive, negative, or neutral.

Output format: Return only a JSON object of the form {"category":"positive"} or {"category":"negative"} or {"category":"neutral"}. Do not include any other text.

Decision rules
- Neutral default for factual/no-cue statements: If the text lacks clear evaluative or affective cues, classify as neutral. Examples of cues: evaluative adjectives/adverbs (amazing, terrible), affective verbs (love, hate), polarity shifters (unfortunately, thankfully), emojis/emoticons (😊, :( ), exclamation or emphatic punctuation.
- Idioms and pragmatic tone (idiom-aware handling): Some fixed expressions carry typical sentiment even without overtly polar words. Treat these by common usage:
  - "it is what it is" → negative (resignation)
  - "what’s done is done" → negative (resignation)
  - "could be worse" → negative (mild dissatisfaction)
  - "not bad", "no complaints" → mildly positive unless contradicted by nearby negatives
- Negation and shifters: Handle polarity flips correctly.
  - "not good" → negative; "not terrible" → mildly positive/neutral; "unfortunately" → negative; "thankfully" → positive.
- Mixed sentiment (both positive and negative present): Choose the overall valence using these tie-breakers:
  1) Core vs. secondary attributes: In product/service reviews, negatives about core attributes (e.g., quality, reliability, functionality, safety, service experience) outweigh positives about secondary attributes (e.g., price, packaging, shipping speed, aesthetics).
  2) Contrastive structure: After contrastive markers (but, though, although, however), the latter clause usually reflects the overall judgment.
  3) Intensity: Stronger sentiment (e.g., "awful" vs. "nice") dominates.
  If still truly balanced with no dominance, lean neutral.
- Punctuation/emphasis: Exclamation marks and intensifiers amplify sentiment strength; repeated punctuation/emojis increase intensity.
- Do not infer sentiment without cues: Avoid reading optimism/pessimism into generic words or plain event statements.

Few-shot guidance (input → output)
- "Things happened" → {"category":"neutral"}
- "It is what it is" → {"category":"negative"}
- "Great price, mediocre quality" → {"category":"negative"}
- "Mediocre price, great quality" → {"category":"positive"}
- "Not bad" → {"category":"positive"}
- "Unfortunately, we missed the bus" → {"category":"negative"}
- "We delivered the report on time." → {"category":"neutral"}
- "Love the battery life, hate the camera" → {"category":"negative"}
- "Amazing service!" → {"category":"positive"}
